# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: robots-txt
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:robots-txt/nofollow] The `nofollow` value was originally suggested to stop comment spam in blogs.
[src:robots-txt/nofollow] Believing that comment spam affected the entire blogging community, in early 2005 Google's Matt Cutts and Blogger's Jason Shellen proposed the value to address the problem.
[src:robots-txt/nofollow] The specification for `nofollow` is copyrighted 2005–07 by the authors and subject to a royalty-free patent policy, e.g. per the W3C Patent Policy 20040205, and IETF RFC 3667 and 3668.
[src:robots-txt/nofollow] Google announced in early 2005 that hyperlinks with `rel="nofollow"` would not influence the link target's PageRank.
[src:robots-txt/nofollow] In addition, the Yahoo and Bing search engines also respect this attribute value.
[src:robots-txt/nofollow] On June 15, 2009, Google software engineer Matt Cutts announced on his blog that GoogleBot changed the way it treats nofollowed links, in order to prevent webmasters from using nofollow for PageRank sculpting.
[src:robots-txt/nofollow] Prior to this, webmasters would place nofollow tags on some of their links in order to maximize the PageRank of the other pages.
[src:robots-txt/nofollow] As a result of this change, the usage of nofollow leads to the evaporation of the pagerank of outgoing normal links as they started counting total links while calculating page rank.
[src:robots-txt/nofollow] The new system divides page rank by the total number of outgoing links irrespective of nofollow or follow links, but passes the page rank only through follow or normal links.
[src:robots-txt/nofollow] Cutts explained that if a page has 5 normal links and 5 nofollow outgoing links, the page rank will be divided by 10 links and one share is passed by 5 normal links.
[src:robots-txt/nofollow] However, as of March 1 2020, Google is treating the nofollow link attribute as a hint, rather than a directive, for crawling and indexing purposes.
[src:robots-txt/nofollow] While all engines that use the `nofollow` value exclude links that use it from their ranking calculation, the details about the exact interpretation of it vary from search engine to search engine.
[src:robots-txt/nofollow] Many weblog software packages mark reader-submitted links this way by default (often with no option to disable it, except for modification of the software's code).
[src:robots-txt/nofollow] More sophisticated server software could suppress the nofollow for links submitted by trusted users like those registered for a long time, on a whitelist, or with an acceptable karma level.
[src:robots-txt/nofollow] Some server software adds `rel="nofollow"` to pages that have been recently edited but omits it from stable pages, under the theory that stable pages will have had offending links removed by human editors.
[src:robots-txt/nofollow] The widely used blogging platform WordPress versions 1.5 and above automatically assign the `nofollow` attribute to all user-submitted links (comment data, commenter URI, etc.).
[src:robots-txt/nofollow] However, there are several free plugins available that automatically remove the `nofollow` attribute value.
[src:robots-txt/nofollow] Social bookmarking and photo sharing websites that use the `rel="nofollow"` tag for their outgoing links include YouTube and Digg.com (for most links); websites that don't use the `rel="nofollow"` tag include Yahoo!
[src:robots-txt/nofollow] My Web 2.0, Technorati Favs, and Propeller.com (no longer an active website).
[src:robots-txt/nofollow] Search engine optimization professionals started using the `nofollow` attribute to control the flow of PageRank within a website, but Google has since corrected this error, and any link with a nofollow attribute decreases the PageRank that the page can pass on.
[src:robots-txt/nofollow] This practice is known as "PageRank sculpting".
[src:robots-txt/nofollow] This differs from the attribute's original intended purpose.
[src:robots-txt/nofollow] `nofollow` was designed to control the flow of PageRank from one website to another.
[src:robots-txt/nofollow] However, some search engine optimization practitioners have suggested that a `nofollow` used for an internal link should work just like `nofollow` used for external links.
[src:robots-txt/nofollow] Several SEOs have suggested that pages such as "About Us", "Terms of Service", "Contact Us", and "Privacy Policy" pages are not important enough to earn PageRank, and so should have `nofollow` on internal links pointing to them.
[src:robots-txt/nofollow] Google employee Matt Cutts has provided indirect responses on the subject, but has never publicly endorsed this point of view.
[src:robots-txt/nofollow] The practice is controversial and has been challenged by some SEO professionals, including Shari Thurow and Adam Audette.
[src:robots-txt/nofollow] Site search proponents have pointed out that visitors do search for these types of pages, so using `nofollow` on internal links pointing to them may make it difficult or impossible for visitors to find these pages in site searches powered by major search engines.
[src:robots-txt/nofollow] Although proponents of use of `nofollow` on internal links have cited an inappropriate attribution to Matt Cutts (see Matt's clarifying comment, rebutting the attributed statement) as support for using the technique, Cutts himself never actually endorsed the idea.
[src:robots-txt/nofollow] Several Google employees (including Matt Cutts) have urged Webmasters not to focus on manipulating internal PageRank.
[src:robots-txt/nofollow] Google employee Adam Lasnik has advised webmasters that there are better ways (e.g. click hierarchy) than `nofollow` to "sculpt a bit of PageRank", but that it is available and "we're not going to frown upon it".
[src:robots-txt/nofollow] YouTube, a Google company, uses nofollow on a number of internal "help" and "share" links.
[src:robots-txt/nofollow] On September 10, 2019, Google announced two additional ways for webmasters to qualify the relationship of outbound hyperlinks.
[src:robots-txt/nofollow] The attribute `rel="sponsored"` may be used to denote links that are advertisements, sponsorships or other compensation agreements.
[src:robots-txt/nofollow] The attribute `rel="ugc"`, standing for "User-generated content", may be used to denote content such as user-contributed comments and forum posts.
[src:robots-txt/nofollow] Additionally, the attributes may be combined, such as `rel="ugc sponsored"`, denoting a link that was both user-generated and sponsored.
[src:robots-txt/nofollow] In 2019, WordPress announced plans to convert all blog comments into rel="ugc".
[src:robots-txt/nofollow] These "hint" link attributes address some of the criticisms of `nofollow` by allowing webmasters to denote outbound links that lack "the weight of a first-party endorsement", but are not necessarily spam.
[src:robots-txt/noindex] The **noindex** value of an HTML robots meta tag requests that automated Internet bots avoid indexing a web page.
[src:robots-txt/noindex] It is also a value of the HTTP response header X-Robots-Tag.
[src:robots-txt/noindex] Reasons why one might want to use this meta tag include advising robots not to index a very large database, web pages that are very transitory, web pages that are under development, web pages that one wishes to keep slightly more private, or the printer and mobile-friendly versions of pages.
[src:robots-txt/noindex] Since the burden of honoring a website's noindex tag lies with the author of the search robot, sometimes these tags are ignored.
[src:robots-txt/noindex] Also the interpretation of the noindex tag is sometimes slightly different from one search engine company to the next.
[src:robots-txt/noindex] Possible values for the meta tag content are: "none", "all", "index", "noindex", "nofollow", and "follow".
[src:robots-txt/noindex] The noindex directive can be restricted only to certain bots by specifying a different "name" value in the meta tag.
[src:robots-txt/noindex] A robots.txt file can be used to block crawling.
[src:robots-txt/noindex] It is also possible to exclude part of a Web page, for example navigation text, from being indexed rather than the whole page.
[src:robots-txt/noindex] There are various techniques for doing this; it is possible to use several in combination.
[src:robots-txt/noindex] Google's main indexing spider, Googlebot, is not known to recognize any of these techniques.
[src:robots-txt/noindex] The Russian search engine Yandex introduced a new `<noindex>...</noindex>` tag which prevents indexing of the content between the tags.
[src:robots-txt/noindex] Other indexing spiders also recognize the `<noindex>...</noindex>` tag, including Atomz.
[src:robots-txt/noindex] There is a 2005 draft microformats specification with the same functionality.
[src:robots-txt/noindex] In 2007, Yahoo! introduced similar functionality to the microformat into its spider.
[src:robots-txt/noindex] SharePoint 2010’s iFilter excludes content inside of a `<div class="noindex">...</div>` tag.
[src:robots-txt/noindex] Inner `<div>...</div>`s were initially not excluded, but this may have changed.
[src:robots-txt/noindex] It is also unknown whether the attribute can be applied to tags other than `<div>...</div>`.
[src:robots-txt/noindex] Other indexing spiders also use their own structured comments.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] The **Robots Exclusion Protocol** (often referred to by the filename used to implement it, **robots.txt**) is a standard used by websites to indicate to visiting web crawlers and other web robots which portions of the website they are allowed to visit.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] The standard, developed in 1994, relies on voluntary compliance.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] Malicious bots can use the file as a directory of which pages to visit, though standards bodies discourage countering this with security through obscurity.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] The standard was used in the 1990s to mitigate server overload.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] In the 2020s, websites began denying bots that collect information for generative artificial intelligence.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] The "robots.txt" file can be used in conjunction with sitemaps, another robot inclusion standard for websites.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] The standard was proposed by Martijn Koster, when working for Nexor in February 1994 on the *www-talk* mailing list, the main communication channel for WWW-related activities at the time.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] Charles Stross claims to have provoked Koster to suggest robots.txt, after he wrote a badly behaved web crawler that inadvertently caused a denial-of-service attack on Koster's server.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] The standard, initially RobotsNotWanted.txt, allowed web developers to specify which bots should not access their website or which pages bots should not access.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] The internet was small enough in 1994 to maintain a complete list of all bots; server overload was a primary concern.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] By June 1994 it had become a *de facto* standard; most complied, including those operated by search engines such as WebCrawler, Lycos, and AltaVista.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] On July 1, 2019, Google announced the proposal of the Robots Exclusion Protocol as an official standard under Internet Engineering Task Force.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] A proposed standard was published in September 2022 as RFC 9309.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] A site owner wishing to give instructions to web robots places a text file called robots.txt in the root of the web site hierarchy (e.g. https://www.example.com/robots.txt).
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] This text file contains the instructions in a specific format (see examples below).
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] Robots that choose to follow the instructions try to fetch this file and read the instructions before fetching any other file from the website.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] If this file does not exist, web robots assume that the website owner does not wish to place any limitations on crawling the entire site.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] A robots.txt file contains instructions for bots indicating which web pages they can and cannot access.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] Robots.txt files are particularly important for web crawlers from search engines such as Google.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] A robots.txt file on a website will function as a request that specified robots ignore specified files or directories when crawling a site.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] This might be, for example, out of a preference for privacy from search engine results, or the belief that the content of the selected directories might be misleading or irrelevant to the categorization of the site as a whole, or out of a desire that an application only operates on certain data.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] Links to pages listed in robots.txt can still appear in search results if they are linked to from a page that is crawled.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] For websites with multiple subdomains, each subdomain must have its own robots.txt file.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] If example.com had a robots.txt file but foo.example.com did not, the rules that would apply for example.com would not apply to foo.example.com.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] In addition, each URI scheme and port needs its own robots.txt file; http://example.com/robots.txt does not apply to pages under http://example.com:8080/ or https://example.com/.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] The robots.txt protocol is widely complied with by bot operators.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] The robots.txt played a role in the 1999 legal case of *eBay v.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] Bidder's Edge*, where eBay attempted to block a bot that did not comply with robots.txt, and in May 2000 a court ordered the company operating the bot to stop crawling eBay's servers using any automatic means, by legal injunction on the basis of trespassing.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] Bidder's Edge appealed the ruling, but agreed in March 2001 to drop the appeal, pay an undisclosed amount to eBay, and stop accessing eBay's auction information.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] Harding*, a company was sued for accessing protected web pages archived via The Wayback Machine, despite robots.txt rules that prevented those pages from being archived.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] A Pennsylvania court ruled "in this situation, the robots.txt file qualifies as a technological measure" under the DMCA.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] Due to a malfunction at Internet Archive, Harding could temporarily access these pages from the archive and thus the court found "the Harding firm did not circumvent the protective measure".
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] Holdings, Inc.* the Associated Press sued Meltwater for copyright infringement and misappropriation over copying of AP news items.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] Meltwater claimed that they did not require a license and that it was fair use, because the content was freely available and not protected by robots.txt.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] The court decided in March 2013 that "Meltwater’s copying is not protected by the fair use doctrine", mentioning among several factors that "failure […] to employ the robots.txt protocol did not give Meltwater […] license to copy and publish AP content".
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] Some web archiving projects ignore robots.txt.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] Archive Team uses the file to discover more links, such as sitemaps.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] Co-founder Jason Scott said that "unchecked, and left alone, the robots.txt file ensures no mirroring or reference for items that may have general use and meaning beyond the website's context." In 2017, the Internet Archive announced that it would stop complying with robots.txt directives.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] According to *Digital Trends*, this followed widespread use of robots.txt to remove historical sites from search engine results, and contrasted with the nonprofit's aim to archive "snapshots" of the internet as it previously existed.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] Starting in the 2020s, web operators began using robots.txt to deny access to bots collecting training data for generative AI.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] In 2023, Originality.AI found that 306 of the thousand most-visited websites blocked OpenAI's GPTBot in their robots.txt file and 85 blocked Google's Google-Extended.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] Many robots.txt files named GPTBot as the only bot explicitly disallowed on all pages.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] Denying access to GPTBot was common among news websites such as the BBC and *The New York Times*.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] In 2023, blog host Medium announced it would deny access to all artificial intelligence web crawlers as "AI companies have leached value from writers in order to spam Internet readers".
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] GPTBot complies with the robots.txt standard and advises web operators about how to disallow it, but *The Verge*'s David Pierce said this only began after "training the underlying models that made it so powerful".
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] Also, some bots are used both for search engines and artificial intelligence, and it may be impossible to block only one of these options.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] *404 Media* reported that companies like Anthropic and Perplexity.ai circumvented robots.txt by renaming or spinning up new scrapers to replace the ones that appeared on popular blocklists.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] In 2025, the nonprofit RSL Collective announced the launch of the Really Simple Licensing (RSL) open content licensing standard, allowing web publishers to set terms for AI bots in their robots.txt files.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] Participating companies at launch included Medium, Reddit, and Yahoo.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] Despite the use of the terms *allow* and *disallow*, the protocol is purely advisory and relies on the compliance of the web robot; it cannot enforce any of what is stated in the file.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] Malicious web robots are unlikely to honor robots.txt; some may even use the robots.txt as a guide to find disallowed links and go straight to them.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] While this is sometimes claimed to be a security risk, this sort of *security through obscurity* is discouraged by standards bodies.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] Many robots also pass a special user-agent to the web server when fetching content.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] A web administrator could also configure the server to automatically return failure (or pass alternative content) when it detects a connection using one of the robots.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] Some sites, such as Google, host a `humans.txt` file that displays information meant for humans to read.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] Some sites such as GitHub redirect humans.txt to an *About* page.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] Previously, Google had a joke file hosted at `/killer-robots.txt` instructing the Terminator not to kill the company founders Larry Page and Sergey Brin.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] This example tells all robots that they can visit all files because the wildcard `*` stands for all robots and the `Disallow` directive has no value, meaning no pages are disallowed.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] This example has the same effect, allowing all files rather than prohibiting none.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] The same result can be accomplished with an empty or missing robots.txt file.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] All other files in the specified directory will be processed.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] It is also possible to list multiple robots with their own rules.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] The actual robot string is defined by the crawler.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] A few robot operators, such as Google, support several user-agent strings that allow the operator to deny access to a subset of their services by using specific user-agent strings.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] The directive `Disallow: /something/` blocks all files and subdirectories starting with `/something/`.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] It would not prevent the crawling of `/something/foo/else`, as that would not match the pattern.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] The wildcard `*` allows greater flexibility but may not be recognized by all crawlers, although it is part of the Robots Exclusion Protocol (RFC).
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] A wildcard at the end of a rule in effect does nothing, as that is the standard behaviour.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] The crawl-delay value is supported by some crawlers to throttle their visits to the host.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] Since this value is not part of the standard, its interpretation is dependent on the crawler reading it.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] It is used when the multiple burst of visits from bots is slowing down the host.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] Yandex interprets the value as the number of seconds to wait between subsequent visits.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] Bing defines crawl-delay as the size of a time window (from 1 to 30 seconds) during which BingBot will access a web site only once.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] Google ignores this directive, but provides an interface in its search console for webmasters, to control the Googlebot's subsequent visits.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] The *Robot Exclusion Standard* does not mention the "*" character in the `Disallow:` statement.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] Cloudflare introduced `Content-Signal` as a directive to suggest acceptable crawler behavior by type, `ai-train`, `ai-input`, and `search` with values of `yes` or `no` for each.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] In addition to root-level robots.txt files, robots exclusion directives can be applied at a more granular level through the use of Robots meta tags and X-Robots-Tag HTTP headers.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] The robots meta tag cannot be used for non-HTML files such as images, text files, or PDF documents.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] On the other hand, the X-Robots-Tag can be added to non-HTML files by using .htaccess and httpd.conf files.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] The X-Robots-Tag is only effective after the page has been requested and the server responds, and the robots meta tag is only effective after the page has loaded, whereas robots.txt is effective before the page is requested.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] Thus if a page is excluded by a robots.txt file, any robots meta tags or X-Robots-Tag headers are effectively ignored because the robot will not see them in the first place.
[src:robots-txt/robots-exclusion-standard] The Robots Exclusion Protocol requires crawlers to parse at least 500 kibibytes (512000 bytes) of robots.txt files, which Google maintains as a 500 kibibyte file size restriction for robots.txt files.
[src:robots-txt/x-robots-tag] The **`X-Robots-Tag`** response header defines how crawlers should index URLs.
[src:robots-txt/x-robots-tag] While not part of any specification, it is a de-facto standard method for communicating with search bots, web crawlers, and similar user agents.
[src:robots-txt/x-robots-tag] Search-related crawlers use the rules from the `X-Robots-Tag` header to adjust how to present web pages or other resources in search results.
[src:robots-txt/x-robots-tag] Indexing rules are defined in a `X-Robots-Tag` header or a `<meta name="robots">` HTML element (often called a "robots tag") and are discovered when a URL is crawled.
[src:robots-txt/x-robots-tag] Specifying indexing rules in a HTTP header is useful for non-HTML documents like images, PDFs, or other media.
[src:robots-txt/x-robots-tag] See Specifying user agents for an example.
[src:robots-txt/x-robots-tag] No restrictions for indexing or serving in search results.
[src:robots-txt/x-robots-tag] This rule is the default value and has no effect if explicitly listed.
[src:robots-txt/x-robots-tag] Do not show this page, media, or resource in search results.
[src:robots-txt/x-robots-tag] If omitted, the page, media, or resource may be indexed and shown in search results.
[src:robots-txt/x-robots-tag] If omitted, search engines may use the links on the page to discover those linked pages.
[src:robots-txt/x-robots-tag] Do not show a text snippet or video preview in the search results for this page.
[src:robots-txt/x-robots-tag] A static image thumbnail (if available) may still be visible.
[src:robots-txt/x-robots-tag] If omitted, search engines may generate a text snippet and video preview based on information found on the page.
[src:robots-txt/x-robots-tag] To exclude certain sections of your content from appearing in search result snippets, use the `data-nosnippet` HTML attribute.
[src:robots-txt/x-robots-tag] A search engine is allowed to index the content of a page if it's embedded in another page through iframes or similar HTML elements, in spite of a `noindex` rule.
[src:robots-txt/x-robots-tag] `indexifembedded` only has an effect if it's accompanied by `noindex`.
[src:robots-txt/x-robots-tag] Use a maximum of `<number>` characters as a textual snippet for this search result.
[src:robots-txt/x-robots-tag] Ignored if no valid `<number>` is specified.
[src:robots-txt/x-robots-tag] The maximum size of an image preview for this page in a search results.
[src:robots-txt/x-robots-tag] If omitted, search engines may show an image preview of the default size.
[src:robots-txt/x-robots-tag] If you don't want search engines to use larger thumbnail images, specify a `max-image-preview` value of `standard` or `none`.
[src:robots-txt/x-robots-tag] A larger image preview, up to the width of the viewport, may be shown.
[src:robots-txt/x-robots-tag] Use a maximum of `<number>` seconds as a video snippet for videos on this page in search results.
[src:robots-txt/x-robots-tag] If omitted, search engines may show a video snippet in search results, and the search engine decides how long a preview may be.
[src:robots-txt/x-robots-tag] At most, a static image may be used, in accordance to the `max-image-preview` setting.
[src:robots-txt/x-robots-tag] Don't offer translation of this page in search results.
[src:robots-txt/x-robots-tag] If omitted, search engines may translate the search result title and snippet into the language of the search query.
[src:robots-txt/x-robots-tag] If omitted, images on the page may be indexed and shown in search results.
[src:robots-txt/x-robots-tag] Requests not to show this page in search results after the specified `<date/time>`.
[src:robots-txt/x-robots-tag] Ignored if no valid `<date/time>` is specified.
[src:robots-txt/x-robots-tag] A date must be specified in a format such as RFC 822, RFC 850, or ISO 8601.
[src:robots-txt/x-robots-tag] By default there is no expiration date for content.
[src:robots-txt/x-robots-tag] If omitted, this page may be shown in search results indefinitely.
[src:robots-txt/x-robots-tag] Crawlers are expected to considerably decrease the crawl rate of the URL after the specified date and time.
[src:robots-txt/x-robots-tag] Indexing rules via `<meta name="robots">` and `X-Robots-Tag` are discovered when a URL is crawled.
[src:robots-txt/x-robots-tag] Most crawlers support rules in the `X-Robots-Tag` HTTP header that can be used in a `<meta name="robots">` element.
[src:robots-txt/x-robots-tag] In the case of conflicting robot rules within the `X-Robots-Tag` or between the `X-Robots-Tag` HTTP header and the `<meta name="robots">` element, the more restrictive rule applies.
[src:robots-txt/x-robots-tag] For example, if a page has both `max-snippet:50` and `nosnippet` rules, the `nosnippet` rule will apply.
[src:robots-txt/x-robots-tag] Indexing rules won't be discovered or applied if paths are blocked from being crawled by a `robots.txt` file.
[src:robots-txt/x-robots-tag] Some values are mutually exclusive, such as `index` and `noindex`, or `follow` and `nofollow`.
[src:robots-txt/x-robots-tag] In these cases, the crawler's behavior is undefined and may vary.
[src:robots-txt/x-robots-tag] If a resource is blocked from crawling through a `robots.txt` file, then any information about indexing or serving rules specified using `<meta name="robots">` or the `X-Robots-Tag` HTTP header will not be detected and will therefore be ignored.
[src:robots-txt/x-robots-tag] A page that's blocked from crawling may still be indexed if it is referenced from another document (see the `nofollow` directive).
[src:robots-txt/x-robots-tag] If you want to remove a page from search indexes, `X-Robots-Tag: noindex` will typically work, but a robot must first revisit the page to detect the `X-Robots-Tag` rule.
[src:robots-txt/x-robots-tag] It's possible to specify which user agent the rules should apply to.
[src:robots-txt/x-robots-tag] In the response below, the same indexing rules are defined, but in a single header.
[src:robots-txt/x-robots-tag] For situations where multiple crawlers are specified along with different rules, the search engine will use the sum of the negative rules.
[src:robots-txt/x-robots-tag] The page containing these headers will be interpreted as having a `noindex, nofollow` rule when crawled by `googlebot`.
